SALES ANALYSIS BASED ON CUSTOMER’S DEMOGRAPHICS AND COMPANY’S CAMPAIGNS¶

BUSINESS PROBLEM:¶

To identify the majority of the customer segments generating revenue, in which product portfolio does the sales increase, to understand which campaign has resulted in generating more revenue to the company and also to understand the company’s performance in various countries.

DATA DICTIONARY¶

ID:- ID of the customer

Year_Birth:- Date of birth of the customer

Education:- Education background of the customer

Marital_Status:- Marital status of the customer

INCOME:- Income of the customers

Kidhome:- Kids of the customers

Teen home:- Teens in the house of customers

Dt_Customer:- Date of purchase of the products

Recency:- Number of days since last purchase

MntWines:- Amount spend on wines products

MntFruits:- Amount spend on fruits products

MntMeatProducts:- Amount spend on meat products

MntFishProducts:- Amount spend on fish products

MntSweetProducts:- Amount spend on sweet products

MntGoldProds:- Amount spend on gold products

NumDealsPurchases:- Number of purchases made with discount

NumWebPurchases:- Number of purchases made from websites

NumCatalogPurchases:- Number of purchases made using catalogue

NumStorePurchases:- Number of purchases made from stores

NumWebVisitsMonth:- Number of visits to company’s website in the last months

AcceptedCmp1:- 1 if customers accepted

AcceptedCmp2:- 1 if customers accepted

AcceptedCmp3:- 1 if customers accepted

AcceptedCmp4:- 1 if customers accepted

AcceptedCmp5:- 1 if customers accepted

Response:- One if customers accepted in last campaign

Complain:- One of the customers complained

Country:- Countries of the sales

In [14]:
df['Dt_Customer'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Dt_Customer'])
df['Purchase_year']= df['Dt_Customer'].dt.year
df['Age']= df['Purchase_year']-df['Year_Birth']

The Dt_Customer variable contains the date of customer purchases the products. So i have extracted the only year and from that I have derived a variable of the AGE of the customers by taking the difference between purchase_year and year_birth.

In [15]:
Feature_nan= [features for features in df.columns if df[features].isnull().sum()>1]
for feature in Feature_nan:
    print(feature, np.round(df[feature].isnull().mean(),4),'% missing values')
for feature in Feature_nan:
    median_value= df[feature].median()
    df[feature+ 'nan']=np.where(df[feature].isnull(),1,0)
    df[feature].fillna(median_value,inplace=True)
df[Feature_nan].isnull().sum()

INCOME 0.0107 % missing values

INCOME    0
dtype: int64

The Income variable has missing data of 0.0107%. So I have imputed with the median value of the variable. The median is not influenced with the outliers.

From the graphs, I understood that the income is more based on education, reflecting the number of dependents.
